<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is lean body mass?", answer: "Lean body mass (LBM) is your total body weight minus your fat mass. It includes muscle, bones, organs, skin, blood, water, and everything in your body that is not stored fat. LBM is a more useful indicator of fitness than total weight because it reflects the metabolically active tissue that burns calories and contributes to physical performance. A higher lean body mass relative to total weight indicates a healthier body composition." },
  { question: "How is lean body mass calculated from body fat percentage?", answer: "If you know your body fat percentage, lean body mass is calculated simply as: LBM = Total Weight x (1 - Body Fat Percentage / 100). For example, if you weigh 80 kg with 20% body fat, your fat mass is 16 kg and your lean body mass is 64 kg. This is the most accurate method if you have a reliable body fat measurement from a DEXA scan, bioelectrical impedance, or other testing method." },
  { question: "What is the Boer formula for lean body mass?", answer: "The Boer formula (1984) estimates lean body mass using weight and height without requiring a body fat measurement. For males: LBM = 0.407 x weight(kg) + 0.267 x height(cm) - 19.2. For females: LBM = 0.252 x weight(kg) + 0.473 x height(cm) - 48.3. It is considered one of the most accurate estimation formulas available and is widely used in clinical settings." },
  { question: "Why does lean body mass matter for fitness?", answer: "Lean body mass determines your basal metabolic rate — more lean mass means you burn more calories at rest. It also directly correlates with physical strength, athletic performance, and bone density. When dieting, preserving lean mass is critical; losing muscle instead of fat reduces metabolism and makes weight regain more likely. Tracking LBM helps ensure your diet and exercise program is building muscle while losing fat." },
  { question: "How can I increase my lean body mass?", answer: "To increase lean body mass, combine progressive resistance training (strength training) with adequate protein intake of 1.6-2.2 grams per kilogram of body weight per day. Eat in a slight caloric surplus (200-400 calories above TDEE) and prioritize sleep for recovery. Compound exercises like squats, deadlifts, bench press, and rows are most effective for building lean mass. Consistency over months and years is key — lean mass is built slowly at a rate of about 0.25-0.5 kg per month for intermediate lifters." }
]) %>

